The President of the United States released a statement on the 45th anniversary of the Apollo 11 moon landing. He recognized the bravery of the three astronauts, Neil Armstrong, Buzz Aldrin, and Michael Collins, and thanked them for their contributions to American ingenuity and human achievement. The President also acknowledged their families for their support and highlighted their role as advocates, role models, and educators who have inspired generations of Americans. He mentioned that NASA, under Administrator Bolden's leadership, is continuing to build on this legacy by preparing for future missions to deep space, including visits to an asteroid and eventually the surface of Mars. The President credited President Kennedy for his vision in setting the United States on a course for the moon and praised the spirit of service of all those who have worked on the Apollo program and pushed the boundaries of space and scientific discovery.